article.headline: Injured Francis leads Lobos with 14 points
article.story:
ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Despite an injured ankle, Jana Francis scored a career-high 14 points and tied her career record for rebounds with seven as New Mexico (No. 25 AP) beat San Francisco 63-52 on Friday night.

Francis helped keep the Lobos (9-1) afloat in the second half when they hit just three shots from the field. She had 10 points after the break, including eight from the free-throw line.

"With her playing well, that helped us a whole bunch. She had a sprained ankle all week long but she gutted it up," said New Mexico coach Don Flanagan, who earned his 200th victory Friday.

Francis played a career-high 31 minutes and had her left ankle encased in ice following the game.

"She showed a lot of toughness this week," Flanagan said.

Mandi Moore added 10 points for the Lobos.

San Francisco (6-7) was led by Dominique Carter, who finished with two 3-pointers and 14 points. Toni Russell added 10 points, including three 3s.

After taking a 36-21 halftime lead, New Mexico hit just one of its first 15 shots from the floor to open the second half. San Francisco was able to creep within 43-36 on a 3-pointer by Russell with 11:05 left.

Francis then went on a 7-0 run for the Lobos. Five of her points came from the line after she missed her first two foul shots.

"I know I can hit free throws," she said. "I just don't know what I was doing on those first two. So I thought, 'I'm going to make the next ones.'"

The Lobos shot 14 percent from the field during the second half, compared to San Francisco's 41 percent.

"All of sudden we can't shoot," Flanagan said. "It's hard to find highlights in there."

New Mexico started strong and it looked like it was going to turn the game into a rout, taking a 36-15 lead with 2:08 remaining. But when the shots didn't go down in the second half, New Mexico became tentative on offense.

While Moore acknowledged that the Lobos weren't being aggressive on the offensive end, she said she wasn't worried.

"This team responds to challenges, you know. If somebody comes at us hard, we'll get it together and go right back at them," she said.
